Proof by [[Principle of Mathematical Induction|induction]]:\nFor all $n \in \N$, let $\map P n$ be the [[Definition:Proposition|proposition]]: 
 :$\displaystyle \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^n i^2 = \frac {n \paren {n + 1} \paren {2 n + 1} } 6$\nWhen $n = 0$, we see from the definition of [[Definition:Vacuous Summation|vacuous sum]] that: 
 :$0 = \displaystyle \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^0 i^2 = \frac {0 \paren 1 \paren 1} 6 = 0$ 
 and so $\map P 0$ holds.\n=== Basis for the Induction ===\nWhen $n = 1$: 
 :$\displaystyle \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^1 i^2 = 1^2 = 1$\nNow, we have: 
 :$\displaystyle \frac {n \paren {n + 1} \paren {2 n + 1} } 6 = \frac {1 \paren {1 + 1} \paren {2 \times 1 + 1} } 6 = \frac 6 6 = 1$ 
 and $\map P 1$ is seen to hold.\nThis is our [[Definition:Basis for the Induction|basis for the induction]].\n=== Induction Hypothesis ===\nNow we need to show that, if $\map P k$ is true, where $k \ge 1$, then it logically follows that $\map P {k + 1}$ is true.\nSo this is our [[Definition:Induction Hypothesis|induction hypothesis]]: 
 :$\displaystyle \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^k i^2 = \frac {k \paren {k + 1} \paren {2 k + 1} } 6$\nThen we need to show: 
 :$\displaystyle \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^{k + 1} i^2 = \frac {\paren {k + 1} \paren {k + 2} \paren {2 \paren {k + 1} + 1} } 6$\n=== Induction Step ===\nThis is our [[Definition:Induction Step|induction step]]:\nUsing the properties of summation, we have: 
 :$\displaystyle \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^{k + 1} i^2 = \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^k i^2 + \paren {k + 1}^2$\nWe can now apply our [[Sum of Sequence of Squares/Proof by Induction#Induction Hypothesis|induction hypothesis]], obtaining: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^{k + 1} i^2 
 | r = \frac {k \paren {k + 1} \paren {2 k + 1} } 6 + \paren {k + 1}^2 
 | c = 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = \frac {k \paren {k + 1} \paren {2 k + 1} + 6 \paren {k + 1}^2} 6 
 | c = 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = \frac {\paren {k + 1} \paren {k \paren {2 k + 1} + 6 \paren {k + 1} } } 6 
 | c = 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = \frac {\paren {k + 1} \paren {2 k^2 + 7 k + 6} } 6 
 | c = 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = \frac {\paren {k + 1} \paren {k + 2} \paren {2 \paren {k + 1} + 1} } 6 
 | c = 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nSo $\map P k \implies \map P {k + 1}$ and the result follows by the [[Principle of Mathematical Induction]].\nTherefore: 
 : $\displaystyle \forall n \in \N: \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^n i^2 = \frac {n \paren {n + 1} \paren {2 n + 1} } 6$\n{{qed}}

