Let $\mathbb P$ be a [[Definition:Finite Set|finite set]] of [[Definition:Prime Number|prime numbers]].\nConsider the number: 
 :$\displaystyle n_p = \paren {\prod_{p \mathop \in \mathbb P} p} + 1$\nTake any $p_j \in \mathbb P$.\nWe have that: 
 : $\displaystyle p_j \divides \prod_{p \mathop \in \mathbb P} p$\nHence: 
 :$\displaystyle \exists q \in \Z: \prod_{p \mathop \in \mathbb P} p = q p_j$\nSo: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = n_p 
 | r = q p_j + 1 
 | c = [[Division Theorem]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto 
 | l = n_p 
 | o = \perp 
 | r = p_j 
 | c = {{Defof|Coprime Integers}} 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nSo $p_j \nmid n_p$.\nThere are two possibilities: 
 :$(1): \quad n_p$ is [[Definition:Prime Number|prime]], which is not in $\mathbb P$. 
 :$(2): \quad n_p$ is [[Definition:Composite Number|composite]].\nBut from [[Positive Integer Greater than 1 has Prime Divisor]], it must be divisible by ''some'' prime.\nThat means it is divisible by a prime which is not in $\mathbb P$.\nSo, in either case, there exists at least one [[Definition:Prime Number|prime]] which is not in the original set $\mathbb P$ we created.\n{{qed}} 
