In the definition of a [[Definition:Group|group]], the [[Definition:Group Axioms|axioms]] for the existence of an [[Definition:Identity Element|identity element]] and for [[Definition:Closed Algebraic Structure|closure]] under taking [[Definition:Inverse Element|inverses]] can be replaced by the following two axioms: 
 : Given a group $G$, there exists at least one [[Definition:Element|element]] $e \in G$ such that $e$ is a [[Definition:Left Identity|'''left identity''']]; 
 : For any element $g$ in a group $G$, there exists at least one [[Definition:Left Inverse Element|'''left inverse''']] of $g$.\nAlternatively, we can also replace the aforementioned axioms with the following two: 
 : Given a group $G$, there exists at least one [[Definition:Element|element]] $e \in G$ such that $e$ is a [[Definition:Right Identity|'''right identity''']]; 
 : For any element $g$ in a group $G$, there exists at least one [[Definition:Right Inverse Element|'''right inverse''']] of $g$.\nThus we can formulate the group axioms as either of the following:

