=== Necessary Condition ===\nLet $\RR$ be both [[Definition:Symmetric Relation|symmetric]] and [[Definition:Antisymmetric Relation|antisymmetric]]\nSuppose $\RR \not \subseteq \Delta_S$.\nThen: 
 :$\exists \tuple {x, y} \in \RR: x \ne y$\nBut then as $\RR$ is [[Definition:Symmetric Relation|symmetric]]: 
 :$\tuple {y, x} \in \RR$\nSo we have: 
 :$\tuple {x, y} \in \RR$ 
 and: 
 :$\tuple {y, x} \in \RR$ 
 where $x \ne y$.\nThus $\RR$ is not [[Definition:Antisymmetric Relation|antisymmetric]], contrary to hypothesis.\nSo our assumption that $\RR \not \subseteq \Delta_S$ is false.\nThat is: 
 :$\RR \subseteq \Delta_S$\nThe result follows by definition of [[Definition:Coreflexive Relation/Definition 2|coreflexive]].\n{{qed|lemma}}\n=== Sufficient Condition ===\nLet $\RR$ be [[Definition:Coreflexive Relation|coreflexive]].\nThen: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = \tuple {x, y} 
 | o = \in 
 | r = \RR 
 }}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto 
 | l = x 
 | r = y 
 | c = Definition of [[Definition:Coreflexive Relation|Coreflexive Relation]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto 
 | l = \tuple {x, y} 
 | r = \tuple {y, x} 
 | c = [[Equality of Ordered Pairs]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto 
 | l = \tuple {y, x} 
 | o = \in 
 | r = \RR 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}} 
 and so by definition $\RR$ is [[Definition:Symmetric Relation|symmetric]].\nLet $\tuple {x, y} \in \RR$ and $\tuple {y, x} \in \RR$.\nFrom the above, this can happen only when $x = y$.\nThat is, by definition, $\RR$ is [[Definition:Antisymmetric Relation|antisymmetric]].\nSo $\RR$ is both [[Definition:Symmetric Relation|symmetric]] and [[Definition:Antisymmetric Relation|antisymmetric]].\nHence the result.\n{{qed}}

