 :$\exists x, y \in S: \exists z \in T: \tuple {x, z} \in T, \tuple {y, z} \in T, x \ne y$ 
 and of course $\set x \subseteq S, \set y \subseteq S$.\nSo: 
 :$z \in \RR \sqbrk {\set x}$ 
 :$z \in \RR \sqbrk {\set y}$ 
 and so by definition of [[Definition:Set Intersection|intersection]]: 
 :$z \in \RR \sqbrk {\set x} \cap \RR \sqbrk {\set y}$\nBut: 
 :$\set x \cap \set y = \O$\nThus from [[Image of Empty Set is Empty Set]]: 
 :$\RR \sqbrk {\set x \cap \set y} = \O$ 
 and so: 
 :$\RR \sqbrk {\set x \cap \set y} \ne \RR \sqbrk {\set x} \cap \RR \sqbrk {\set y}$\n{{qed|lemma}}\n=== Necessary Condition ===\nLet $\RR$ be [[Definition:One-to-Many Relation|one-to-many]].\nFrom [[Image of Intersection under Relation]], we already have: 
 :$\RR \sqbrk {S_1 \cap S_2} \subseteq \RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2}$\nSo we just need to show: 
 :$\RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2} \subseteq \RR \sqbrk {S_1 \cap S_2}$\nLet $t \in \RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2}$.\nThen: 
