=== Existence ===\nTo show that $\oplus$ as defined above exists:\nLet $u, v \in S$, and let $x = f \left({u}\right), y = f \left({v}\right)$.\nThen as $f$ is a [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]], $u = f^{-1} \left({x}\right), v = f^{-1} \left({y}\right)$.\nThus: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = f \left({u \circ v}\right) 
 | r = f \left({f^{-1} \left({x}\right) \circ f^{-1} \left({y}\right)}\right) 
 | c = Definition of $x$ and $y$ 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = f \left({f^{-1} \left({x}\right)}\right) \oplus f \left({f^{-1} \left({y}\right)}\right) 
 | c = [[Definition:Morphism Property|Morphism Property]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = x \oplus y 
 | c = [[Inverse of Inverse of Bijection]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = f \left({u}\right) \oplus f \left({v}\right) 
 | c = Definition of $x$ and $y$ 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nIt is seen that $f$ is an [[Definition:Isomorphism (Abstract Algebra)|isomorphism]] as required.\n{{qed|lemma}}\n=== Uniqueness ===\nLet $f$ be the [[Definition:Isomorphism (Abstract Algebra)|isomorphism]] whose existence has been proven [[Transplanting Theorem#Existence|above]].\nThus: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = f \left({f^{-1} \left({x}\right) \circ f^{-1} \left({y}\right)}\right) 
 | r = f \left({f^{-1} \left({x}\right)}\right) \oplus f \left({f^{-1} \left({y}\right)}\right) 
 | c = [[Definition:Morphism Property|Morphism Property]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = \left({f \circ f^{-1} \left({x}\right)}\right) \oplus \left({f \circ f^{-1} \left({y}\right)}\right) 
 | c = Definition of [[Definition:Composition of Mappings|Composite Mapping]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = \left({I_T \left({x}\right)}\right) \oplus \left({I_T \left({y}\right)}\right) 
 | c = [[Bijection has Left and Right Inverse]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = x \oplus y 
 | c = Definition of [[Definition:Identity Mapping|Identity Mapping]] 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nSo, if $\oplus$ is an [[Definition:Binary Operation|operation]] on $T$ such that $f$ is an [[Definition:Isomorphism (Abstract Algebra)|isomorphism]] from $\left({S, \circ}\right) \to \left({T, \oplus}\right)$, then $\oplus$ must be defined as by this theorem, and there can be no other such [[Definition:Binary Operation|operations]].\n{{qed}}

f^{-1} \left({x}\right) & : x \in T_2 
 \end{cases}$\nBecause $T_1$ and $S_2$ are [[Definition:Disjoint Sets|disjoint]], $h$ can be seen to be a [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]].\nWhat $h$ is doing is that it effectively "slots" $T_1$ into the gap in $S_2$ that was taken up by the removed $T_2$.\nWe are going to show that $\left({T_1, \oplus_1}\right)$ is [[Definition:Submagma|embedded]] in $\left({S_1, *_1}\right)$.\nThe [[Definition:Binary Operation|operation]] $*_1$ is defined as the [[Transplanting Theorem|transplant of $*_2$ under $h$]].\nThus by the [[Transplanting Theorem]]: 
 :$\forall x, y \in S_1: x *_1 y = h \left({h^{-1} \left({x}\right) *_2 h^{-1} \left({y}\right)}\right)$\nLet $x, y \in T_1$.\nThen, from the definition of $h$ above: 
 :$h^{-1} \left({x}\right) = \left({f^{-1} \left({x}\right)}\right)^{-1} = f \left({x}\right)$ 
 and similarly: 
 :$h^{-1} \left({y}\right) = f \left({y}\right)$\nSo: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = x *_1 y 
 | r = h \left({f \left({x}\right) *_2 f \left({y}\right)}\right) 
 | c = [[Transplanting Theorem]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = h \left({f \left({x}\right) \oplus_2 f \left({y}\right)}\right) 
 | c = as $*_2$ is [[Definition:Submagma|embedded]] in $\oplus_2$ 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = h \left({f \left({x \oplus_1 y}\right)}\right) 
 | c = [[Definition:Morphism Property|Morphism Property of $\oplus_1$ under $f$]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = f^{-1} \left({f \left({x \oplus_1 y}\right)}\right) 
 | c = Definition of $h$ on elements of $T_1$ 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = x \oplus_1 y 
 | c = [[Inverse of Inverse of Bijection]] 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}} 
 proving that $x \oplus_1 y$ is [[Definition:Closed Algebraic Structure|closed]].\nThus: 
 : $\left({T_1, \oplus_1}\right) \subseteq \left({S_1, *_1}\right)$ 
 that is, $\left({T_1, \oplus_1}\right)$ is [[Definition:Submagma|embedded]] in $\left({S_1, *_1}\right)$.\nNow, let $g = h^{-1}$.\nBy the definition of $*_1$, $g$ is an [[Definition:Isomorphism (Abstract Algebra)|isomorphism]] from $\left({S_1, *_1}\right)$ onto $\left({S_2, *_2}\right)$.\nThen: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = x \in T_1 
 | o = \implies 
 | r = f \left({x}\right) \in T_2 
 | c = by definition of $f$ 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \implies 
 | r = h \left({f \left({x}\right)}\right) = f^{-1} \left({f \left({x}\right)}\right) = x 
 | c = by definition of $h$ 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nThus: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = g \left({x}\right) 
 | r = g \left({h \left({f \left({x}\right)}\right)}\right) 
 | c = from above 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = h^{-1} \left({h \left({f \left({x}\right)}\right)}\right) 
 | c = by definition of $g$ 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = f \left({x}\right) 
 | c = [[Inverse of Inverse of Bijection]] 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nSo $g$ is an [[Definition:Extension of Mapping|extension]] of $f$.\nWe have therefore proved that the embedding theorem holds when $T_1$ and $S_2$ are [[Definition:Disjoint Sets|disjoint]].\n{{qed|lemma}}\nNext, suppose $T_1$ and $S_2$ are ''not'' [[Definition:Disjoint Sets|disjoint]].\nWe can use [[Exists Bijection to a Disjoint Set]] to assume the existence of a [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]] $k: S_2 \to S_3$ such that $S_3 \cap T = \varnothing$.\nLet $*'$ be the [[Transplanting Theorem|transplant of $*$ under $k$]].\nLet: 
 :$T_3 = \left\{{k \left({x}\right): x \in T_2}\right\}$\nThen: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = x, y \in T_3 
 | o = \implies 
 | r = k^{-1} \left({x}\right), k^{-1} \left({y}\right) \in T_2 
 | c = by definition of $k$ 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \implies 
 | r = k^{-1} \left({x}\right) * k^{-1} \left({y}\right) \in T_2 
 | c = by definition of $*$ in $T_2$ 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \implies 
 | r = x *' y = k \left({k^{-1} \left({x}\right) * k^{-1} \left({y}\right)}\right) \in T_3 
 | c = [[Transplanting Theorem]] 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nSo $T_3$ is closed under $*'$.\nLet $*' {\restriction_{T_3} }$ be the [[Definition:Operation Induced by Restriction|operation on $T_3$ induced by $*'$]].\nThen $\left({T_3, *' {\restriction_{T_3} } }\right)$ is embedded in $\left({S_3, *'}\right)$.\nThus $k \circ f$ is an [[Definition:Isomorphism (Abstract Algebra)|isomorphism]] from $\left({T_1, \oplus_1}\right)$ onto $\left({T_3, *' {\restriction_{T_3} } }\right)$. 
 $S_3$ has been constructed so as to be [[Definition:Disjoint Sets|disjoint]] from $T_1$.\nIn such a case it has already been shown that the embedding theorem holds.\nThat is: 
 :$(1): \quad$ there exists a [[Definition:Magma|magma]] $\left({S_1, *_1}\right)$ [[Definition:Submagma|containing $\left({T_1, \oplus_1}\right)$ algebraically]] 
 :$(2): \quad$ there exists an [[Definition:Isomorphism (Abstract Algebra)|isomorphism]] $g_1$ from $\left({S_1, *_1}\right)$ to $\left({S_3, \oplus_1}\right)$ [[Definition:Extension of Mapping|extending]] $k \bullet f$.\nLet $g = k^{-1} \bullet g_1$.\nLet $x \in T$.\nThen: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = g \left({x}\right) 
 | r = k^{-1} \left({g_1 \left({x}\right)}\right) 
 | c = definition of $g$ 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = k^{-1} \left({k \left({f \left({x}\right)}\right)}\right) 
 | c = as $g_1$ extends $k \bullet f$ 
 }}\n{{eqn | r = f \left({x}\right) 
 | c = [[Inverse of Inverse of Bijection]] 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}} 
 and so $g$ [[Definition:Extension of Mapping|extends]] $f$.\nAs $k$ is an [[Definition:Isomorphism (Abstract Algebra)|isomorphism]] from $\left({S_2, *}\right)$ onto $\left({S_3, *'}\right)$, then: 
 :$(1): \quad g$ is an [[Definition:Isomorphism (Abstract Algebra)|isomorphism]] from $\left({S_1, *_1}\right)$ onto $\left({S_2, *}\right)$ 
 :$(2): \quad g$ [[Definition:Extension of Mapping|extends]] $f$.\nHence the result.\n{{qed}} 
