 :$\left({x \circ z}\right)\circ' \left({w \circ y}\right)^{-1} \in S \circ' C^{-1}$ 
 proving that $S \circ' C^{-1}$ is [[Definition:Closed Algebraic Structure|closed]].\nTherefore by [[Subsemigroup Closure Test]]: 
 :$S \circ' C^{-1}$ is a [[Definition:Subsemigroup|subsemigroup]] of $\left({T, \circ'}\right)$ 
 and thus a [[Definition:Semigroup|semigroup]].\n{{qed|lemma}}\nIt remains to be shown that $\circ'$ is a [[Definition:Commutative Operation|commutative operation]].\nLet $\left({x \circ' y^{-1} }\right)$ and $\left({z \circ' w^{-1} }\right)$ be two arbitrary [[Definition:Element|elements]] of $S \circ' C^{-1}$.\nBy [[Element Commutes with Product of Commuting Elements]], $x, y, z, w$ all [[Definition:Commute|commute]] with each other under $\circ$.\nAs $\circ'$ is an [[Definition:Extension of Operation|extension]] of $\circ$, it follows that $x, y, z, w$ also all [[Definition:Commute|commute]] with each other under $\circ'$.\nThen: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | l = \left({x \circ' y^{-1} }\right) \circ' \left({z \circ' w^{-1} }\right) 
 | r = x \circ' \left({y^{-1} \circ' z}\right) \circ' w^{-1} 
 | c = [[Definition:Associative Operation|Associativity of $\circ'$]] 
